01:16:59,252 --> 01:17:01,198
I mean, as an actress. 
- Yes, that's what I mean.

1802
01:17:01,779 --> 01:17:03,827
I thought she was Mallory's discovery.

1803
01:17:38,086 --> 01:17:39,381
Oh, Good evening, Miss Martin.

1804
01:17:39,620 --> 01:17:40,851
My, but you look lovely!

1805
01:17:40,851 --> 01:17:43,291
Thank you, I'm so excited I can hardly talk.

1806
01:17:43,291 --> 01:17:44,369
And who isn't?

1807
01:17:47,194 --> 01:17:47,817
Oh, Johnny,

1808
01:17:47,941 --> 01:17:49,121
You better call half hour.

1809
01:17:49,424 --> 01:17:50,777
<i> Half hour, please!</i>

1810
01:17:51,385 --> 01:17:53,696
High ball glasses. Cocktail glasses. Cards...

1811
01:17:53,696 --> 01:17:54,091
Yes, sir.

1812
01:17:54,298 --> 01:17:56,776
And uh... have the table 'bout four foot downstage.

1813
01:17:57,297 --> 01:17:58,811
Oh, hello, Katherine.
- Hello, Joe.

1814
01:17:58,836 --> 01:18:00,540
Take a look at that house. It's sold out.

1815
01:18:00,540 --> 01:18:01,536
<i>Half hour, please.</i>

1816
01:18:01,784 --> 01:18:02,801
Where shall I put these?

1817
01:18:02,801 --> 01:18:03,582
Out in the hall.

1818
01:18:03,582 --> 01:18:04,668
Is that the cord he rehearsed with?

1819
01:18:04,668 --> 01:18:05,216
Yes.

1820
01:18:05,216 --> 01:18:06,196
<i>Andrews.
-</i> Yes, sir.

1821
01:18:06,196 --> 01:18:07,415
How's Mr. Mallory?

1822
01:18:07,431 --> 01:18:08,311
Is he here, yet?

1823
01:18:08,320 --> 01:18:09,312
No, miss.
- What?

1824
01:18:09,671 --> 01:18:11,288
I've been here since 5:30.

1825
01:18:11,313 --> 01:18:14,079
You know how he dreads a New York opening. He's always the last one in.

1826
01:18:14,204 --> 01:18:16,897
Well, even so. Half hour's been called. You better go check on him.

1827
01:18:16,897 --> 01:18:17,555
Very good, sir.

1828
01:18:44,354 --> 01:18:45,224
Hey, you!

1829
01:18:46,310 --> 01:18:47,227
Yes, you!

1830
01:18:47,958 --> 01:18:48,628
Come here.

1831
01:18:54,274 --> 01:18:56,318
I think we've had the pleasure of meeting before.

1832
01:18:56,641 --> 01:18:58,057
I wouldn't call it a pleasure.

1833
01:18:58,503 --> 01:18:59,595
You seeing the show?

1834
01:18:59,991 --> 01:19:01,241
Do you think I'm a sucker?

1835
01:19:01,638 --> 01:19:03,987
Still a blundering, hot-headed fool, aren't you?

1836
01:19:04,621 --> 01:19:07,367
For my part, I'd be very happy if I never had to see you again.

1837
01:19:07,663 --> 01:19:09,695
I think I'll be able to arrange that all right!

1838
01:19:10,021 --> 01:19:12,224
Oh, it isn't as easy as all that.

1839
01:19:13,124 --> 01:19:14,177
You're still in love with her.

1840
01:19:14,791 --> 01:19:16,131
Otherwise, you wouldn't be here.

1841
01:19:16,553 --> 01:19:18,312
Go on in. Maybe you'll learn something.

1842
01:19:19,133 --> 01:19:19,797
From you?

1843
01:19:19,797 --> 01:19:21,918
Oh, don't argue. Do as I say.

1844
01:19:22,507 --> 01:19:24,115
When you hear my curtain speech,

1845
01:19:24,582 --> 01:19:26,274
come back and offer your apologies.

1846
01:19:30,847 --> 01:19:32,841
<i>On stage. Places please.</i>

1847
01:19:35,988 --> 01:19:37,895
<i>On stage. Places please.</i>

1848
01:19:38,269 --> 01:19:39,245
You're late, Mr. Mallory.

1849
01:19:39,245 --> 01:19:41,779
Nonsense. You've got loads of time

1850
01:19:41,779 --> 01:19:42,743
Loads of time.

1851
01:19:49,757 --> 01:19:50,768
My cane, Andrews.

1852
01:19:51,616 --> 01:19:52,352
My gloves.

1853
01:19:53,965 --> 01:19:55,004
My chapeau.

1854
01:19:57,543 --> 01:19:58,653
Are you all right, sir?

1855
01:19:59,950 --> 01:20:01,254
Why, of course, I'm all right.

1856
01:20:01,772 --> 01:20:02,804
Can I get you some coffee, sir?

1857
01:20:02,860 --> 01:20:04,415
No, I don't need any coffee.

1858
01:20:05,167 --> 01:20:07,936
I only had a couple of highballs just to steady my nerves.

1859
01:20:08,929 --> 01:20:10,502
Important night, Andrews!

1860
01:20:10,907 --> 01:20:12,445
The house is sold out.
- Yes, sir.

1861
01:20:13,525 --> 01:20:15,048
Miss Martin in her dressing room?

1862
01:20:15,048 --> 01:20:15,539
Yes, sir.

1863
01:20:18,644 --> 01:20:19,171
Andrews!

1864
01:20:19,830 --> 01:20:20,785
What's my first line?

1865
01:20:21,104 --> 01:20:22,371
"I waited for you in the garden"!

1866
01:20:22,371 --> 01:20:25,518
Oh, yes. Of course. "I waited for you in the garden."

1867
01:20:25,885 --> 01:20:27,865
You know, Andrews. It's the strangest thing

1868
01:20:28,200 --> 01:20:31,482
that I can never remember my first lines on opening night.

1869
01:20:32,539 --> 01:20:35,308
Until I get on the stage, and then it all comes back to me.

1870
01:20:37,776 --> 01:20:38,755
Mr. Mallory!

1871
01:20:38,755 --> 01:20:40,173
Awwww, Andrews.

1872
01:20:43,255 --> 01:20:44,849
You haven't too much time, sir.

1873
01:20:45,248 --> 01:20:47,109
Andrews. Now, you treat me like a child.

1874
01:20:47,566 --> 01:20:50,140
The act runs 6 minutes before I make my entrance.

1875
01:20:50,630 --> 01:20:53,937
And in 6 minutes I can make up for Dr. Jeckyl and Mr. Hyde.

1876
01:21:03,383 --> 01:21:04,940
I wonder if Barry is here.

1877
01:21:05,255 --> 01:21:06,370
He said he wasn't coming.

1878
01:21:06,525 --> 01:21:08,217
Oh, that was for Honey's benefit.

1879
01:21:08,352 --> 01:21:09,785
He isn't fooling her, either.

1880
01:21:10,292 --> 01:21:12,024
May I have Charlie's autograph?

1881
01:21:14,353 --> 01:21:15,566
This is forgery, you know.

1882
01:21:16,145 --> 01:21:17,377
Charlie may sue me.

1883
01:21:17,419 --> 01:21:19,163
Thank you. Thank you, Mrs. Bergen.

1884
01:21:19,202 --> 01:21:20,502
Oh, I'm not Mrs. Bergen.

1885
01:21:20,753 --> 01:21:22,240
I'm Mrs. McCarthy!

1886
01:21:26,049 --> 01:21:29,161
The scene is the drawing room of Richard Storm's Long Island estate.

1887
01:21:29,585 --> 01:21:31,420
And evening in late Spring.

1888
01:21:48,971 --> 01:21:49,795
See who that is.

1889
01:21:51,556 --> 01:21:52,230
Yes?

1890
01:21:52,253 --> 01:21:53,150
Kay: <i>May I come in?</i>

1891
01:21:53,446 --> 01:21:56,136
<i>Not just now, Miss Martin. Mr. Mallory's dressing.</i>

1892
01:21:56,175 --> 01:21:58,097
I just wanted to thank him for the flowers.

1893
01:21:58,264 --> 01:22:00,088
And tell him I'm going to do my best.

1894
01:22:00,379 --> 01:22:02,224
Thanks, my dear! Good luck!

1895
01:22:02,687 --> 01:22:03,584
Same to you.

1896
01:22:12,705 --> 01:22:13,818
Bottle snatcher!

1897
01:22:14,897 --> 01:22:18,409
I feel it's too ghastly. I never even suspected anything until he bought her here.

1898
01:22:18,724 --> 01:22:21,067
Brought who here, Charlotte? The house is full of people.

1899
01:22:21,067 --> 01:22:22,249
<i>Mary Draper!</i>

1900
01:22:22,450 --> 01:22:23,344
Good luck. 
-

1901
01:22:23,383 --> 01:22:24,391
Thanks, Joe!

1902
01:22:24,991 --> 01:22:26,043
I need it.

1903
01:22:26,043 --> 01:22:27,629
You don't know what tonight means to me.

1904
01:22:28,062 --> 01:22:29,095
<i>...and I won't have it!...</i>

1905
01:22:29,151 --> 01:22:30,676
"And when they're cheering,

1906
01:22:30,914 --> 01:22:32,893
"I'll come out and put my arm around you.

1907
01:22:33,331 --> 01:22:34,974
"And I'll tell them who you are.

1908
01:22:35,853 --> 01:22:36,619
What did you say?

1909
01:22:36,659 --> 01:22:37,733
Nothing, Joe.

1910
01:22:37,926 --> 01:22:38,823
Wait and see.

1911
01:22:38,863 --> 01:22:41,162
<i>...I don't see why you need any help to wreck this one...</i>

1912
01:22:41,498 --> 01:22:43,268
Jenny.
- I'm going home.

1913
01:22:43,570 --> 01:22:46,480
The idea of you dragging me here away from my own guests,

1914
01:22:46,539 --> 01:22:48,258
simply because you two--
- Shh!

1915
01:23:00,895 --> 01:23:03,151
Miss Draper. Mrs. Stopherson, my aunt.

1916
01:23:03,207 --> 01:23:04,082
How do you do?

1917
01:23:04,318 --> 01:23:06,437
Richard has told me a great deal about you.

1918
01:23:06,837 --> 01:23:08,905
Charlotte has told me a great deal about <i>you</i>.

1919
01:23:09,411 --> 01:23:11,554
Forgive me for leaving you now. I have guests waiting.

1920
01:23:11,792 --> 01:23:14,403
I'd like to have a cup of tea with you, if you're still here tomorrow.

1921
01:23:14,403 --> 01:23:15,524
I should love that.

1922
01:23:16,202 --> 01:23:17,172
Good bye, Jenny.

1923
01:23:17,412 --> 01:23:18,164
Good bye, Charlotte.

1924
01:23:18,303 --> 01:23:19,310
Sorry, I can't help.

1925
01:23:19,529 --> 01:23:21,323
Au revoir, Miss Draper. 
- Good bye.

1926
01:23:22,880 --> 01:23:24,353
Where is everybody?
-At supper.

1927
01:23:24,500 --> 01:23:27,073
Richard, too? 
- Miss Draper, I'd like to have a talk with you.

1928
01:23:27,541 --> 01:23:28,505
<i>I'm going to be very frank.</i>

1929
01:23:28,706 --> 01:23:30,083
<i>- I wish you would.</i>

1930
01:23:30,312 --> 01:23:31,379
<i> Your staying here...</i>

1931
01:23:32,104 --> 01:23:33,448
<i>Mr. Mallory. On stage.</i>

1932
01:23:33,448 --> 01:23:34,483
Just a moment!

1933
01:23:40,260 --> 01:23:41,522
I can't do it, Andrews.

1934
01:23:41,870 --> 01:23:42,723
I can't do it.

1935
01:23:43,716 --> 01:23:46,496
10 years of those wretched pictures have done something to me.

1936
01:23:47,340 --> 01:23:49,189
It isn't like carrying a play in New York.

1937
01:23:49,645 --> 01:23:52,804
But they're ready to tear anybody apart who has the temerity to come back from Hollywood.

1938
01:23:52,804 --> 01:23:54,898
But you were excellent in Cleveland, sir.

1939
01:23:57,170 --> 01:23:58,966
Mr. Mallory, please hurry.

1940
01:23:59,716 --> 01:24:01,102
Give me that first line again, Andrews.

1941
01:24:01,250 --> 01:24:03,141
"I waited for you in the garden"! 
- Yes. I've got it.

1942
01:24:03,678 --> 01:24:05,273
"I waited for you in the garden."

1943
01:24:06,032 --> 01:24:07,640
"I hated to leave, because

1944
01:24:08,171 --> 01:24:10,226
"I wanted to see your face in the moonlight.

1945
01:24:10,567 --> 01:24:11,332
What's next, Andrews?

1946
01:24:11,332 --> 01:24:13,132
"Where it's quiet and we can be alone"

1947
01:24:13,182 --> 01:24:14,265
<i>...Richard is an artist...</i>

1948
01:24:14,498 --> 01:24:16,844
...<i>it's important that his family look after his interests...</i>

1949
01:24:16,998 --> 01:24:18,531
...<i>when he chooses to ignore them...</i>

1950
01:24:18,862 --> 01:24:20,750
<i>I'm sorry you don't like me, Miss Dor.</i>

1951
01:24:21,139 --> 01:24:23,442
<i>...because I'm leaving here tonight and never coming back.</i>

1952
01:24:23,783 --> 01:24:25,140
<i>...and Richard is coming with me.</i>

1953
01:24:25,140 --> 01:24:26,239
Good luck, Mr. Mallory.

1954
01:24:26,239 --> 01:24:27,053
Thanks, Joe.

1955
01:24:27,053 --> 01:24:27,720
<i>...all your life...</i>

1956
01:24:28,540 --> 01:24:29,916
<i>...You're much too young for Richard...</i>

1957
01:24:30,398 --> 01:24:31,768
<i>...You're not suited to each other...</i>

1958
01:24:32,499 --> 01:24:34,202
<i>That may be. But he loves me</i>

1959
01:24:34,684 --> 01:24:35,581
<i>...and I love him...</i>

1960
01:24:36,268 --> 01:24:38,927
<i>...and there's nothing you can do or say that can change that...</i>

1961
01:24:39,384 --> 01:24:40,801
<i>Don't be too sure of that!</i>

1962
01:24:59,210 --> 01:25:00,977
These fools. They're confusing me.

1963
01:25:04,520 --> 01:25:06,143
I waited for you in the garden.

1964
01:25:06,734 --> 01:25:09,762
I hated to leave because I wanted to see your face in the moonlight.

1965
01:25:10,019 --> 01:25:13,337
Richard, can't we go away from here where it's quiet and we can be alone?

1966
01:25:13,823 --> 01:25:15,000
We can be alone here.

1967
01:25:15,000 --> 01:25:15,989
Please, Richard.

1968
01:25:16,297 --> 01:25:17,706
I'm not comfortable here.

1969
01:25:22,947 --> 01:25:23,963
<i>What's my next line?</i>

1970
01:25:25,283 --> 01:25:26,463
[Kay whispers] 
<i>"But, Mary, this is my home".</i>

1971
01:25:28,124 --> 01:25:29,037
Mary.

1972
01:25:29,671 --> 01:25:30,845
This is my home!

1973
01:25:31,340 --> 01:25:33,017
I want you to love it as I do.

1974
01:25:33,629 --> 01:25:34,892
Soon it will be all yours.

1975
01:25:35,299 --> 01:25:37,290
We've a lot to talk over before that.

1976
01:25:37,526 --> 01:25:38,822
Please, Richard. Let's go.

1977
01:25:39,611 --> 01:25:41,055
Whatever you say, my dear.

1978
01:25:41,213 --> 01:25:43,077
I'll get my things and meet you in the car.

1979
01:25:47,195 --> 01:25:48,354
What's the matter with him, Andrews?

1980
01:25:48,855 --> 01:25:50,431
It's just nerves, Miss. That's all.

1981
01:25:50,843 --> 01:25:52,224
You were very nice, Miss.

1982
01:25:52,682 --> 01:25:53,781
Thank you, Andrews.

1983
01:25:54,259 --> 01:25:56,170
...<i>Say, Richard. I didn't know you were down...</i>

1984
01:25:56,440 --> 01:25:57,806
<i>...the others have all gone to supper...</i>

1985
01:25:58,237 --> 01:25:59,158
<i>Have they?</i>

1986
01:26:00,191 --> 01:26:00,848
What's happening?

1987
01:26:01,013 --> 01:26:02,024
...<i>Did you ring, sir?</i>

1988
01:26:02,418 --> 01:26:03,436
...<i>Oh, uh, yes...</i>

1989
01:26:03,701 --> 01:26:06,124
Bring me my hat and coat, please, and have my car waiting.

1990
01:26:06,126 --> 01:26:06,839
Yes, sir.

1991
01:26:09,091 --> 01:26:10,932
You're not going out anywhere this evening are you?

1992
01:26:11,269 --> 01:26:12,154
Ah, yes.

1993
01:26:12,893 --> 01:26:14,515
Yes, I'm going into town.

1994
01:26:14,798 --> 01:26:16,216
Have you forgotten your guests?

1995
01:26:17,360 --> 01:26:18,160
Guests?

1996
01:26:24,237 --> 01:26:26,095
Crowd: What's the matter with Mallory?
- He's drunk.

1997
01:26:28,753 --> 01:26:29,732
[Off-stage whisper]
<i>"Make my apologies."</i>

1998
01:26:30,659 --> 01:26:32,083
Can't you go in the morning?

1999
01:26:34,006 --> 01:26:35,093
Mallory: <i> What's my next line?</i>

2000
01:26:37,154 --> 01:26:38,979
<i>"Charlotte, can't I even go into town?"</i>

2001
01:26:39,580 --> 01:26:40,271
Charlotte!

2002
01:26:40,520 --> 01:26:42,980
Can't I even go into town without consulting you?

2003
01:26:44,670 --> 01:26:46,652
<i>"Will you stop interfering in my life."</i>

2004
01:26:47,432 --> 01:26:48,713
Go out there. He's coded.

2005
01:26:52,302 --> 01:26:53,168
Your coat, sir.

2006
01:26:53,459 --> 01:26:54,688
Will you put it on?
- Oh, thank you...

2007
01:26:59,838 --> 01:27:01,409
<i>Cut it down to his exit speech!</i>

2008
01:27:01,757 --> 01:27:02,263
<i>"Richard!"</i>

2009
01:27:02,999 --> 01:27:03,855
Richard!

2010
01:27:04,288 --> 01:27:05,653
You can't go on like this.

2011
01:27:06,490 --> 01:27:08,025
I've stood it as long as I intend to.

2012
01:27:08,096 --> 01:27:09,755
This girl's presence in this place

2013
01:27:09,910 --> 01:27:10,997
is, is...
<i>[audience titters]</i>

2014
01:27:11,177 --> 01:27:12,908
it's an intolerable humiliation!

2015
01:27:27,781 --> 01:27:29,007
<i>Help him with his coat.</i>

2016
01:27:30,031 --> 01:27:31,466
<i> Help him. with. his. coat.</i>

2017
01:27:32,260 --> 01:27:33,660
<i>...Richard, can I help you?</i>

2018
01:27:36,452 --> 01:27:38,928
You never seem to enjoy yourself as much, Charlotte,

2019
01:27:39,488 --> 01:27:41,292
as when you're making me--
<i>- You're going the wrong way.</i>

2020
01:27:41,852 --> 01:27:42,599
<i>This way.</i>

2021
01:27:46,879 --> 01:27:49,676
You never seem to enjoy yourself as much a---
<i>- Oh!</i>

2022
01:27:51,863 --> 01:27:53,406
Bring down the curtain. Bring it down.

2023
01:28:26,584 --> 01:28:27,542
What's happened?

2024
01:28:27,716 --> 01:28:28,757
<i>Ladies and gentlemen...</i>

2025
01:28:29,962 --> 01:28:30,929
<i>due to the...</i>

2026
01:28:31,181 --> 01:28:33,032
<i>sudden illness of Mr. Mallory,</i>

2027
01:28:34,119 --> 01:28:37,453
<i>I regret to announce that we're unable to continue the performance this evening.</i>

2028
01:28:38,972 --> 01:28:41,016
<i>Your money will be refunded at the box-office.</i>

2029
01:29:09,045 --> 01:29:09,645
Well.

2030
01:29:11,970 --> 01:29:13,350
Why don't you say it, Katherine?

2031
01:29:15,307 --> 01:29:16,858
Why don't you say that I failed you?

2032
01:29:19,228 --> 01:29:21,110
Why don't you say that I'm a drunken has-been?

2033
01:29:49,423 --> 01:29:52,714
I'd stay here for a little while, sir, if I were you. I wouldn't try to go out.

2034
01:30:05,613 --> 01:30:06,602
Was that Mallory?

2035
01:30:06,655 --> 01:30:07,857
I didn't see his face.

2036
01:30:08,227 --> 01:30:09,399
It looked like him.

2037
01:30:30,090 --> 01:30:31,126
Well.

2038
01:30:31,701 --> 01:30:33,671
You're the first to congratulate me.

2039
01:30:34,303 --> 01:30:36,258
What did you think of my night of triumph?

2040
01:30:39,839 --> 01:30:41,345
Stop it. Stop it!

2041
01:30:57,069 --> 01:30:58,069
Just a minute!

2042
01:31:05,166 --> 01:31:06,850
<i>I can't imagine what happened.</i>

2043
01:31:06,850 --> 01:31:08,293
<i>Guess he drank himself out of it...</i>

2044
01:31:08,293 --> 01:31:09,544
<i>I liked what I saw of the girl.</i>

2045
01:31:11,193 --> 01:31:12,157
<i>He's smashed, is all.</i>

2046
01:31:12,157 --> 01:31:14,013
<i>It would have been funny, if it weren't so tragic.</i>

2047
01:31:22,794 --> 01:31:24,478
HURRY!

2048
01:31:24,746 --> 01:31:27,556
Yes. Certainly, it was Mallory. I saw him myself.

2049
01:31:27,904 --> 01:31:30,191
He was hit by a taxi. I tell you and badly injured.

2050
01:31:30,191 --> 01:31:31,146
Was Kay Martin with him?

2051
01:31:31,434 --> 01:31:33,443
Well stick there. Call me if anything happens.

2052
01:31:38,270 --> 01:31:39,051
Hey, Suzy.

2053
01:31:39,789 --> 01:31:41,738
Find out where Kay Martin lives. Get her on the phone.

2054
01:31:42,143 --> 01:31:43,214
How should I know?

2055
01:31:53,579 --> 01:31:55,412
Where shall I put this stuff from the dressing room?

2056
01:31:55,412 --> 01:31:57,512
Oh, anywhere Edgar. Just leave it there.

2057
01:31:59,456 --> 01:32:00,329
Shall I answer?

2058
01:32:00,510 --> 01:32:01,545
Please.

2059
01:32:02,004 --> 01:32:02,824
Hello.

2060
01:32:04,335 --> 01:32:05,216
Reporters.

2061
01:32:06,492 --> 01:32:09,700
Miss Martin has nothing to say. She won't talk to any reporters.

2062
01:32:13,461 --> 01:32:14,606
It's nearly 11, Edgar.

2063
01:32:14,606 --> 01:32:16,088
I know. I've got to beat it.

2064
01:32:16,088 --> 01:32:17,440
I'm on the air in a half hour.

2065
01:32:17,862 --> 01:32:18,996
Good luck, Edgar.

2066
01:32:19,510 --> 01:32:20,778
Thanks a lot for everything.

2067
01:32:21,096 --> 01:32:22,789
Kay, if I could only tell you how sorry--

2068
01:32:22,793 --> 01:32:25,137
All right, Lancelot. You've said your piece. Get going.

2069
01:32:25,426 --> 01:32:27,364
You know what Charlie will do if you're late.
- What?

2070
01:32:27,419 --> 01:32:30,113
He'll clip you Bergen. He'll <i>mow</i> you down!

2071
01:32:34,537 --> 01:32:37,268
We'll do what we can. It's... useless to operate.

2072
01:32:37,993 --> 01:32:40,523
Opiates to relieve his pain is about all we can do at the present.

2073
01:32:40,847 --> 01:32:42,319
Have you notified his family?

2074
01:32:42,817 --> 01:32:44,328
Mr. Mallory has no family, sir.

2075
01:32:45,208 --> 01:32:46,825
He's calling for someone named Katherine.

2076
01:32:46,920 --> 01:32:49,035
Oh, yes. Do you think he might see her, sir?

2077
01:32:49,652 --> 01:32:53,134
Well, there's no reason why Mr. Mallory shouldn't do anything he wants to now.

2078
01:32:53,134 --> 01:32:54,134
Thank you, sir.

2079
01:32:54,531 --> 01:32:58,619
<i>Oh, Doctor! You know the...</i>

2080
01:33:00,680 --> 01:33:04,151
Listen, operator. I told you. Miss Martin isn't talking to anybody.

2081
01:33:04,379 --> 01:33:07,036
No, not anybody. She has no statement to make!

2082
01:33:09,951 --> 01:33:12,249
Oh, let them say anything they like.

2083
01:33:12,536 --> 01:33:16,509
Everything that's nasty and mean has already been printed in all those gossip columns.

2084
01:33:17,296 --> 01:33:18,595
What harm can they do now?

2085
01:33:18,595 --> 01:33:20,249
Oh, you mustn't feel like that, Kay.

2086
01:33:21,337 --> 01:33:22,952
Oh, it's time for Edgar. Do you mind?

2087
01:33:22,952 --> 01:33:23,768
Of course, not.

2088
01:33:24,093 --> 01:33:27,041
He'd never forgive us if we didn't listen and tell him how bad he is.

2089
01:33:35,687 --> 01:33:39,136
<i>"And now, ladies and gentlemen, the boys who have New York at their feet!</i>

2090
01:33:39,204 --> 01:33:41,584
<i>"Edgar Bergen and Charlie McCarthy!</i>

2091
01:33:42,689 --> 01:33:44,037
Mr. Bergen,

2092
01:33:44,037 --> 01:33:46,601
before we continue with another broadcast,

2093
01:33:46,773 --> 01:33:48,919
I want you to answer me one question.

2094
01:33:49,276 --> 01:33:51,270
Do I get an increase in my allowance?

2095
01:33:51,914 --> 01:33:55,578
After all, 75 cents a week isn't enough.

2096
01:33:56,440 --> 01:33:57,040
What's that?

2097
01:33:57,478 --> 01:33:58,083
Uh...

2098
01:33:59,106 --> 01:34:01,397
I'm afraid we're not going to be very funny tonight.

2099
01:34:01,563 --> 01:34:02,377
Mr. Bergen?

2100
01:34:02,912 --> 01:34:04,197
I'm afraid not, Charlie.

2101
01:34:05,200 --> 01:34:06,059
Ladies and gentlemen,

2102
01:34:06,366 --> 01:34:08,762
will you forgive us for not being at our best this evening?

2103
01:34:08,844 --> 01:34:11,174
Because a dear friend of ours, a great actor,

2104
01:34:11,486 --> 01:34:12,810
met with a disaster.

2105
01:34:13,359 --> 01:34:14,813
He opened in a new play tonight.

2106
01:34:14,813 --> 01:34:17,378
His first appearance on Broadway in 12 years.

2107
01:34:17,812 --> 01:34:20,004
Because he was nervous, he went up in his lines.

2108
01:34:20,365 --> 01:34:22,724
For the first time in a long and brilliant career,

2109
01:34:22,998 --> 01:34:25,466
the curtain had to be run down on John Mallory.

2110
01:34:26,288 --> 01:34:28,373
Must've been a terrible blow to his pride.

2111
01:34:28,884 --> 01:34:30,862
If only we could tell him that it didn't matter.

2112
01:34:31,160 --> 01:34:33,160
But every man is entitled to one muff.

2113
01:34:33,609 --> 01:34:34,394
But we can't.

2114
01:34:35,027 --> 01:34:37,260
Because 20 minutes after the curtain came down,

2115
01:34:37,659 --> 01:34:39,634
John Mallory was struck by a taxi

2116
01:34:39,897 --> 01:34:41,480
and is now lying close to death.

2117
01:34:42,000 --> 01:34:42,751
Cora!

2118
01:34:42,927 --> 01:34:45,133
If any of his friends are listening in, they ought to go to him.

2119
01:34:45,412 --> 01:34:46,885
He's at the mid-town hospital.

2120
01:34:47,287 --> 01:34:49,674
Mid-town hospital? Where is that?
- Get your coat on. I'll take you.

2121
01:34:59,111 --> 01:35:01,739
Andrews! He's going to be all right, isn't he?

2122
01:35:02,043 --> 01:35:03,552
The reports are exaggerated.

2123
01:35:04,306 --> 01:35:05,532
I'm afraid not, Miss.

2124
01:35:05,984 --> 01:35:07,359
He wants to see you.

2125
01:35:07,580 --> 01:35:09,827
It will make him very happy to know you're here.

2126
01:35:13,678 --> 01:35:15,171
I'll wait for you here.

2127
01:35:33,607 --> 01:35:34,407
Mr. Mallory,

2128
01:35:36,050 --> 01:35:36,934
Andrews...

2129
01:35:38,776 --> 01:35:40,058
call the reporters...

2130
01:35:41,596 --> 01:35:42,645
something I...

2131
01:35:43,572 --> 01:35:44,562
want to tell them...

2132
01:35:45,993 --> 01:35:47,451
I should have done it long ago.

2133
01:35:47,822 --> 01:35:50,213
Mr. Mallory, you were asking for Miss Martin.

2134
01:35:50,718 --> 01:35:51,748
Yes, Andrews.

2135
01:35:53,004 --> 01:35:53,911
Be sure...

2136
01:35:55,010 --> 01:35:56,338
be sure to tell her...

2137
01:35:57,214 --> 01:35:58,463
if you see her...

2138
01:35:59,847 --> 01:36:01,235
how much I love her...

2139
01:36:02,954 --> 01:36:04,817
Darling, I'm here.

2140
01:36:04,990 --> 01:36:05,445
Huh?

2141
01:36:11,303 --> 01:36:12,821
It's Katherine.

2142
01:36:14,239 --> 01:36:15,351
Oh, my darling.

2143
01:36:17,986 --> 01:36:20,308
To think I could be so selfish and cruel!

2144
01:36:20,800 --> 01:36:21,571
Cruel?

2145
01:36:23,115 --> 01:36:23,782
You?

2146
01:36:25,186 --> 01:36:26,103
Darling,

2147
01:36:27,089 --> 01:36:28,803
you've made me happier..

2148
01:36:29,785 --> 01:36:32,046
than all the people I've ever known...

2149
01:36:32,995 --> 01:36:34,811
put together...

2150
01:36:37,397 --> 01:36:38,941
You mustn't cry, dear.

2151
01:36:40,414 --> 01:36:41,543
Mustn't cry.

2152
01:36:45,150 --> 01:36:47,081
<i>I didn't keep my promise, Katherine.</i>

2153
01:36:48,281 --> 01:36:49,977
<i>I didn't tell them about you.</i>

2154
01:36:50,469 --> 01:36:51,644
It doesn't matter.

2155
01:36:53,058 --> 01:36:54,188
But I'm going to.

2156
01:36:55,439 --> 01:36:56,480
Andrews.
- Yes?

2157
01:36:57,302 --> 01:36:58,278
Reporters...

2158
01:36:59,193 --> 01:37:01,169
They're downstairs. Do you want them to come up now?

2159
01:37:01,169 --> 01:37:02,128
Yes! Yes.

2160
01:37:03,222 --> 01:37:04,239
Bring them in. 
- Very good.

2161
01:37:05,106 --> 01:37:06,034
Hurry.

2162
01:37:08,385 --> 01:37:10,364
You must be quiet now. Rest.

2163
01:37:11,095 --> 01:37:11,819
Darling,

2164
01:37:13,232 --> 01:37:14,424
try to forgive me...

2165
01:37:15,229 --> 01:37:17,258
for being such a bad father.

2166
01:37:17,432 --> 01:37:19,139
Oh, darling, you haven't!

2167
01:37:20,206 --> 01:37:21,817
<i>I've never done anything for you...</i>

2168
01:37:22,695 --> 01:37:24,029
<i>as a father should...</i>

2169
01:37:25,684 --> 01:37:27,748
<i>I'm going to tell the world about you.</i>

2170
01:37:30,389 --> 01:37:31,604
Well, at least...

2171
01:37:32,674 --> 01:37:33,791
I can do that.

2172
01:37:36,394 --> 01:37:37,171
Doctor!

2173
01:37:54,380 --> 01:37:55,439
Miss Ryan.

2174
01:37:56,029 --> 01:37:57,835
<i>Hoooh, no!</i>

2175
01:38:02,087 --> 01:38:03,795
Just one moment, please.

2176
01:38:11,195 --> 01:38:14,235
Gentleman, Mr. Mallory has just passed away.

2177
01:38:39,629 --> 01:38:41,228
This goes to Pennsylvania station.

2178
01:38:48,355 --> 01:38:50,510
Katherine, I'm really sorry you're going away.

2179
01:38:50,697 --> 01:38:53,633
Why don't you stay here and do another play for me? Right away.

2180
01:38:54,827 --> 01:38:55,713
I can't.

2181
01:38:56,910 --> 01:38:57,980
Not while I'm...

2182
01:38:57,980 --> 01:39:00,849
I'm... on Roman Holiday for all the gossip columnists.

2183
01:39:01,623 --> 01:39:03,984
I'd feel I were capitalizing on his death.

2184
01:39:04,231 --> 01:39:06,169
But he would have wanted you to go on.

2185
01:39:06,874 --> 01:39:09,565
Well, maybe next year when they've forgotten all about me.

2186
01:39:09,565 --> 01:39:11,061
I'll come back and try again.

2187
01:39:11,449 --> 01:39:12,146
Well,

2188
01:39:12,925 --> 01:39:15,219
whenever you do decide, let me know.

2189
01:39:15,234 --> 01:39:15,900
Thanks.

2190
01:39:16,102 --> 01:39:17,328
You've been very kind.

2191
01:39:17,328 --> 01:39:18,864
If you wanna make that plane, you'd better hurry.

2192
01:39:19,068 --> 01:39:20,235
All set, Kay?

2193
01:39:21,087 --> 01:39:23,204
I think I have everything.
- Shall I take this?

2194
01:39:23,299 --> 01:39:24,364
Please, will you?

2195
01:39:28,219 --> 01:39:29,312
Mr. Bergen.
- Hello, Andrews.

2196
01:39:29,312 --> 01:39:30,491
[indistinguishable]

2197
01:39:30,605 --> 01:39:31,704
Excuse me, please.

2198
01:39:33,358 --> 01:39:34,876
Hello, Andrews.
- Miss Cora.

2199
01:39:35,801 --> 01:39:37,846
Miss Martin, I was so afraid I'd missed you.

2200
01:39:37,846 --> 01:39:39,763
You know I wouldn't go without seeing you.

2201
01:39:40,163 --> 01:39:41,972
I've been going through Mr. Mallory's effects.

2202
01:39:42,533 --> 01:39:45,688
I came across this letter of yours. I thought perhaps you'd like to keep it.

2203
01:39:48,404 --> 01:39:50,176
My letter of introduction.

2204
01:39:52,697 --> 01:39:53,782
Thank you, Andrews.

2205
01:39:54,181 --> 01:39:55,305
You- you won't...

2206
01:39:55,502 --> 01:39:57,265
Not if you don't want me to, Miss.

2207
01:39:57,665 --> 01:40:00,166
But don't you think it might be better for you, if--
 - No, Andrews.

2208
01:40:00,864 --> 01:40:03,633
No one would understand my waiting until now to announce it.

2209
01:40:04,042 --> 01:40:04,503
If..

2210
01:40:04,503 --> 01:40:06,564
If he had told, it would have been different, but...

2211
01:40:07,018 --> 01:40:10,796
If I were to tell now, it would only cause more unpleasant publicity about him and

2212
01:40:11,089 --> 01:40:12,147
I don't want that.

2213
01:40:12,780 --> 01:40:14,089
I understand.

2214
01:40:18,001 --> 01:40:18,912
Allow me.

2215
01:40:18,912 --> 01:40:20,122
Thank you.

2216
01:40:27,375 --> 01:40:28,846
Oh, there's Barry.

2217
01:40:29,790 --> 01:40:30,725
Oh, Miss Martin!

2218
01:40:30,754 --> 01:40:31,986
Miss Martin, could we have a statement, please?

2219
01:40:31,986 --> 01:40:34,095
Please, gentlemen, I have nothing to say.
- Where're you going?

2220
01:40:35,189 --> 01:40:36,459
Hey.
- Barry!

2221
01:40:36,459 --> 01:40:38,709
Where, Miss Martin?

2222
01:40:38,736 --> 01:40:40,524
Beat to the shore, will you, Sparky?

2223
01:40:41,295 --> 01:40:42,756
Just a second. 
- Now, Come on!

2224
01:40:43,351 --> 01:40:45,450
Newspaper bloodhounds!

2225
01:40:46,221 --> 01:40:47,437
Are you going home?

2226
01:40:49,896 --> 01:40:50,741
Kay, darling...

2227
01:40:51,022 --> 01:40:51,779
Yes, Barry.

2228
01:40:52,001 --> 01:40:52,785
I love you.

2229
01:40:53,133 --> 01:40:54,989
I always have and I always will.

2230
01:40:55,458 --> 01:40:58,412
I was a fool. Jealous and suspicious.

2231
01:40:58,855 --> 01:40:59,974
I tried to forget you.

2232
01:41:00,165 --> 01:41:01,686
I never wrecked Honey's life.

2233
01:41:03,848 --> 01:41:07,424
It doesn't seem possible so many things could happen in so short a time.

2234
01:41:09,219 --> 01:41:10,747
And all because of this letter.

2235
01:41:12,222 --> 01:41:16,413
The letter that was to open the doors of fame, success and happiness.

2236
01:41:17,351 --> 01:41:18,199
And now...

2237
01:41:19,003 --> 01:41:20,126
Now, he's dead.

2238
01:41:20,593 --> 01:41:22,250
Did he mean so much to you?

2239
01:41:23,106 --> 01:41:24,919
More than anyone will ever know.

2240
01:41:28,601 --> 01:41:30,848
Then, I guess there's nothing else to say.

2241
01:41:33,427 --> 01:41:34,432
Barry, dear,

2242
01:41:35,453 --> 01:41:36,855
Will you please read this?

2243
01:41:41,372 --> 01:41:42,272
Please.

2244
01:41:51,128 --> 01:41:54,111
Edgar, tell them to hurry or we'll never get to the station in time.

2245
01:41:54,111 --> 01:41:57,526
Yeah, step on it.
- Oh, let's not bother. They'll never go there.

2246
01:41:57,538 --> 01:41:59,004
You're pretty sure, aren't you?

2247
01:41:59,004 --> 01:42:02,890
Listen, Cora. That boy and that girl clicked the first moment they looked at each other.

2248
01:42:02,890 --> 01:42:05,332
It's that kind of a look that will last until eternity.

2249
01:42:05,637 --> 01:42:06,992
My, my! How poetic.

2250
01:42:06,992 --> 01:42:08,567
Oh, shut-up.

2251
01:42:08,866 --> 01:42:11,144
Edgar, is Charlie always going to come between us?

2252
01:42:11,258 --> 01:42:12,547
Ye- How do you like that?

2253
01:42:12,566 --> 01:42:13,822
This is my car!

2254
01:42:13,822 --> 01:42:17,269
Bergen bought it for me, so I wouldn't have to be wrapped up in newspapers

2255
01:42:17,269 --> 01:42:18,309
every time I went out.

2256
01:42:18,320 --> 01:42:20,859
Oh, I'm sorry, Charlie. But you are in the way.

2257
01:42:21,217 --> 01:42:23,671
Yes.
- Mr. Bergen and I have things to discuss.

2258
01:42:23,730 --> 01:42:24,878
Oh, sure, yeah...

2259
01:42:24,878 --> 01:42:27,198
I suppose you want to sit on his lap, huh?

2260
01:42:27,587 --> 01:42:29,635
Charlie.
- Huh?
- Would you be good enough, to...

2261
01:42:29,635 --> 01:42:30,780
No, I wouldn't!

2262
01:42:30,792 --> 01:42:31,788
Don't be a sap.

2263
01:42:32,002 --> 01:42:33,700
As long as I'm between you, you're safe!

2264
01:42:34,003 --> 01:42:37,654
Why if I leave, she'll take you like Grant took Richmond!

2265
01:42:38,112 --> 01:42:41,880
<i> Join hands. In chorus we will sing...</i>

2266
01:42:42,007 --> 01:42:45,096
<i>...through the hot time, do the whole town</i>

2267
01:42:45,096 --> 01:42:47,561
<i> tonight, my baby!</i>

